    {
      "@id": "urn:artigo:3639709",
      "@type": "ArtigoCientifico",
      "identificador": "3639709",
      "temObjetivo": [
        "Stress Detection of Autistic Adults 2:3 The goal of this work is to measure stress in a quantitative manner. This work will be expanded in the future to provide autistic individuals with emotion regulation strategies during interviews."
      ],
      "temProblema": [
        "Current approaches focus on providing feedback and strategies to the interviewee but fail to gather stress data directly or provide stress response-based insights, which are necessary to develop effective stress management strategies and adaptations to the interview that are beneficial to both the interviewee and the interviewer. That is, despite some research on stress training [Hutchinson et al. 2019 ], there is a need for reliable, quantitative measures of stress to better target and sustain existing training [Newsome et al. 2019 ].",
        "That is, despite some research on stress training [Hutchinson et al. 2019 ], there is a need for reliable, quantitative measures of stress to better target and sustain existing training [Newsome et al. 2019 ]. 1 Due to the preference of autistic individuals and their families [Keating et al. n.d.], we have adopted identify-first language for our disability-related terminology."
      ],
      "temMetodologia": [
        "For example, asking structured questions, as opposed to open ended questions, was effective for eliciting memories and personal facts while semantic prompts worked best for personal characteristics, such as those asked for during job interviews. Using visual-verbal prompts with the question broken into sections such as: when it happened, where it happened, and people and objects involved increased recall of information for autistic individuals [Norris et al. 2020 ]."
      ],
      "temContribuicao": [
        "The aforementioned challenges contribute to the high rate of unemployment among Autistic individuals 1 [Fong et al. 2021 ; Whetzel 2014 ], even though a large majority of them report a desire to work [Roux et al. 2017 ; Taylor et al. 2019 ]. Multiple factors impact the ability of autistic individuals to find and maintain employment, including workplace discrimination, anxiety and stress, and challenges in social behavior and communication [Taylor et al. 2019 ; Trakoli 2021 ].",
        "We provide initial insights by developing a visualization tool that allows an understanding of stress response through visualization during the course of a VR-based simulated interview [Adiani et al. 2022 , 2023 ]. Previous publications detail the design of the VR-based simulated interview with stakeholder input and present an overview of data collected and initial The current work presents a novel dataset of physiological data and ground truth stress labels for 15 autistic individuals during CIRVR, a simulated virtual reality interview."
      ],
      "temTrabalhoFuturo": [],
